block content

  +state('Missouri', '/assets/images/flag-missouri.svg', 'The Show Me State', 'August 10, 1821', 'border')

  .intro
    p Like many other state flags, the Missouri flag begins with the Daughters of the American Revolution. They appointed Mary Elizabeth Oliver to lead a committee and in 1908 she brought her design to the state capitol.
    p Her flag competed against another design by Dr. G.H. Holcomb, but ultimately it was chosen as the first (and so far, only) Missouri state flag.
    p It was officially adopted March 22, 1913.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Flag design
      p The Missouri state flag features three horizontal stripes of equal width in red, white, and blue color. At the center, a circular band of blue encompasses the state coat of arms.
    .visual.flag
      img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri.svg')

  .guide.wide
    .content
      h2 Iconography
      ul.visual.icon-list
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-stars.svg')
          h4 24 stars
          p The outer ring of 24 stars represent the states of the Union including Missouri.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-stars2.svg')
          h4 24 more stars
          p 24 more stars are featured, but with one larger at the center representing Missouri as the 24th state.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-bears.svg')
          h4 Bears
          p The supporting bears symbolize the strength and courage of the people of Missouri.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-knight.svg')
          h4 Knight & shield
          p The divided shield, knight’s helmet, and buckle symbolize strength and independence of the state. “United We Stand, Divided We Fall” is a reminder of the strength of the union.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-crescent.svg')
          h4 Crescent
          p The crescent moon represents the immense potential for the future of Missouri.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-eagle.svg')
          h4 Eagle
          p The eagle with olive branch and arrows is borrowed from the Great Seal of the U.S. and commemorates Missouri as part of the nation.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-motto.svg')
          h4 Motto
          p The Latin words “Salus Populi Suprema Lex Esto” translate to “The Welfare of the People Shall Be the Supreme Law,” Missouri’s state motto.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-missouri-icon-date.svg')
          h4 1820
          p The date, in Roman numerals, is 1820 and refers to the year of the Missouri Compromise allowing Missouri to join the Union as a slave state.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Coat of Arms
      p The Missouri coat of arms and state seal have been relatively unchanged since they were designed in 1822 by Judge Robert William Wells.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/coat-of-arms-missouri.jpg')

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Colors
      p While the specific values are not specified, the colors of the Missouri flag do have meaning.
      p The red represents valor, white represents purity, and blue represents vigilance, permanency, and justice.
    .visual
      .colors.primary
        .color
          .sample(class='red')
